		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=22033"><span id=>broneb</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>3 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>I am a newbie to everquest and have played my paladin High Elf to lvl 7&nbsp;&nbsp;(only 2 weeks of work)<br><br>But I did not realize i could invest Training points. Or really i didn't know how to; but that is a different story. <br><br>Where should my training points go.  I use 2h slash and it's a high level   <br>My high levels skills are<br>    2h slash<br>    def   off<br>    sense heading<br>    1h slash is OK<br><br>What is important other than this<br>I would like to keep this character<br><br>Is becoming a blacksmith worth it. I have read articles for the + and the - for it</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >3 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
		   <table class="mform2"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Sun, Jan 21st 1:58 AM 2001 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=6&mid=98003072117790&num=3&page=&post=1&replyto=9800421428399"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=9800421428399></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform2><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=2048"><span id=Sage>SouldragoonFlamingheart</span></a><b><span id=Sage><br>Sage</span></b><br><img src=/shared/user_star_ico.gif height=9 width=9><br>144 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.55]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>You are only able to invest up to 20 points in any trade skill (like blacksmithing and tailoring).&nbsp;&nbsp;For that reason, it is not very useful to invest your skill points in them when you can easily make those points through basic practice at the forge.  Just go buy a whole bunch of sharpening stones and rusty weapons.  Combine the stone and rusty weapon until you make a tarnished weapon.  Your skill will go up into the teens this way.  Once you cannot gain anymore skill in this fashion, start to make metal bits.  They require 2 pieces of small ore and 1 flask of water.  You will screw up alot at first, but you will notice your skill start to go up.  You will go past 20 by the time you master metal bits.  I've always tried to convince people that it might be more worthwhile to spend all of your skill points mastering one obscure language that nobody else knows.  There is no limit for language point investment (up to 200 anyway).<br><br>The best town to practice your smithing is freeport.  Everything you need is not too far away.  Groflah's forge in north freeport sells sharpening stones and bricks of ore.  You can buy water at a number of places.  If you are trying to make metal bits, just do it at the forge right outside of groflah's.  If you need rusty weapons to start out with, you can buy all you need from a shop in east freeport.  I forget the exact name of the shop.  The name has 'resales' in it.  Hallah's Resales.. or something like that.  It's a big sign, so you can't miss it.  Find the tanning/leather shop in east freeport.  There is an alleyway to the side of it.  Take the alleyway back until you see the rusty weapon shop.  Buy rusty daggers because they are the cheapest.  DO NOT go downstairs in this shop.  If you go down the stairs, a dog named scraps will come and whoop you unless you are something like level 20.  I was level 6 when I went down there.  I guess I should go back there now and get my revenge...  it took me 9 deaths to get my body out of harms way.  There is a forge in east freeport, next to the armor shop.  Using that is the quickest way to sharpen weapons.  If both of these forges are ever occupied, there is another forge in north freeport near the bank.  It's a pain to zone unneccesarily, but if you have to, it's there.  Just remember..  later on in your paladin's life, you will more than likely go KoS to the freeport militia.  At that point, your blacksmithing practice will come to an end (in freeport that is).  You will still be able to go to north freeport safely, but you will only be able to make metal bits at groflah's because they don't require any molds to make, like all the other items do.  I guess I should tell you that the molds can be bought at the building right next to the armor shop in east freeport.  Just look up one of the blacksmithing guides at this site, or elsewhere, to see what makes what and what skill you should be to make it.  I can't think of anything much on this subject.  I hope I was helpful.<br><br>Souldragoon Flamingheart<br>40th circle Paladin of Virtue<br>Fennin Ro<br><br>ps  If you play on Fennin, I'd be happy to help your blacksmithing out in the game.  Just look me up.  I'll be playing alot starting feb 14.</p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br><i>Follow virtue, and the virtuous will follow you.</i></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
