		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=16104"><span id=Scholar>Dadin</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br><img src=/shared/user_star_ico.gif height=9 width=9><br>93 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Use training points wisely.&nbsp;&nbsp;What I did was to put only 1 point into each catagory that I had obtained (such as bash) and let the remaining points stack up by using your newly acquired skill during battle.  This way you can save up your points and place them into a skill such as Taloring, smithing, Jewlry, ect.  A word of advice that I later found out is whenever you get your first set of spells, immediatly put 1 training point into conjuration, channeling, evocation (rather the skills that magic is used for) it is very frustrating whenever you spend all your mana casting a basic cure spell and you waste mana on fizzes constantly leaving you oom and with little or no health left. Weapons wise it is easiest at your level to invest one hit point into all of them (1 handed blunt, 1 hand slash, 2 hand slash, 2 hand blunt, and hand to hand) purchase or loot yourself some cheap 1 handed blunt weapon (a splintered club cmoes to mind) and a 2handed blunt weapon (worn great staff) that have a low delay.  Interchange weapons till your skills are maxed, then resort back to your primary weapon.  Doesn't sound like fun but at Level 25+ there are some really great weapons that are out there that are blunt weapons.  I currently have my 2HS , 1HS, and Bash maxed out at all times and am working on my 1HB.  I generally carry alot of weapons on me genarally 3 at one time + a shield.<br><br>Blacksmithing is a very nice skill to have. It is very expensive to start out with, especially as a new player killing the lowly smakes and stuff.  I started blacksmithing when I had around 100pp saved up in the bank.  It may seem like your losing money left and right, but as your stats go up and your are able to make armor you can begin to make the money that you lost back up.  Blacksmithing is something that takes alot of time and becomes very tedious in the beginning as well.  I agree that Freeport is THE place to learn blacksmithing due to the fact that everything you need is right around the corner.  I agree that sharpening rusty weapons is the way to go, but if your cheap like me you wouldn't purchase them.  go out to the nwebie area and loot them (off the corpse of the moster you killed of course).  That way you gain exp, and save yourself some precious gold coin that you desperatly need for when you have to make metal bits.  Freeprt is the city I learned smithing at and it is the city that I go back to to increase my skill, you would think the Dwarven City of Kaladim would be the place for smithing (due to the fact that Dwarves are synonomous with smithing in every story that you've read) but this isn't true in Everquest.  It is possible to smith in the city but the neccesary molds and ores are spread out all over Kaladim and Butcherblock.  But now I am rambling so I'll stop now.</p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Dadin <br>54th Cavalier<br>Honored Circle on Xev<br><br>Dwarven Thane<br>Hellwinds - Palomides </td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
